{{Infobox artist | name = Mahmoud Hammad | image = MahmoudHammad.jpg | imagesize = 220px | caption = Mahmoud Hammad | birth_name = | birth_date = 1923 | birth_place = [[Jarabulus]], [[Syria]] | death_date = 1988 | death_place = Damascus | nationality = Syrian | field = [[Painting]], Print-making, engraving | training = [[Accademia di belle arti di Roma]] | movement = [[Hurufiyya movement]] | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = [[Derrie Fakhoury]] | website = [http://www.mahmoudhammad.com/ Mahmoud Hammad] }}
[[File:3Z5M8 L03220-139.jpg|thumbnail]] [[File:Malula.jpg|thumbnail]]
'''Mahmoud Hammad''' (born 1923 in [[Jarabulus]], [[Syria]]) is a Syrian [[Painting|painter]] and pioneer of modern Syrian art
==Life and career== He studied art at the [[Accademia di belle arti di Roma]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accademiabelleartiroma.it/|title=Accademia Di Belle Arti Di Roma}}</ref> between 1953 and 1957. He focused on the art of engraving and especially the art medals. After completing his studies he returned to [[Damascus]] in 1960 and taught as professor at the Fine Arts Faculty of Damascus since its creation. From 1970 until 1980, he became dean at the Fine Arts Faculty of Damascus.<ref name="Sothebys">{{cite web|title=Mahmoud Hammad 'DAD' (LETTER D)|url=http://www.sothebys.com/en/auctions/ecatalogue/lot.51.html/2015/contemporary-art-doha-do1501|website=Sothebys|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref> In 1939, he started exhibiting his work throughout most Arab countries, Europe and the United States. In 1948, he received first prize in Arts in Damascus Exhibition, in 1957, first prize at the competition of the city of Naples, and in 1959, first prize at the competition of Ministry of Culture in United Arab Republic. In his work, Hammad uses the geometry of elementary forms to express the dynamic spirit of the Arabic letter. Among circles, squares, rectangles, determined by the color, the letter appears with liberty to end a profound silence.
His work has been shown in exhibitions at museums such as the [[Jordan National Gallery of Fine Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://universes-in-universe.org/eng/nafas/articles/2003/modern_art_from_the_arab_world|title=Modern Art from the Arab World |last=Ali|first=Wijdan|date=December 2003|publisher=Nafas art magazine|accessdate=2009-04-22}}</ref>
He was married to [[Derrie Fakhoury]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
==Work== Hammad uses Arabic phrases in abstract compositions. He interweaves the letters to create a mass of geometric forms. He tries to use forms that are familiar in Islamic culture. This use of Arabic calligraphy as a graphic form places him within the ''Hurufiyah Art Movement.'' <ref>Mavrakis, N., "The Hurufiyah Art Movement in Middle Eastern Art," ''McGill Journal of Middle Eastern Studies Blog,'' Online: https://mjmes.wordpress.com/2013/03/08/article-5/</ref> The art historian, [[Wijdan Ali]] describes his style of painting as 'Abstract Calligraphy' within the Hurufiyya movement. <ref> Ali, W., ''Modern Islamic Art: Development and Continuity,'' University of Florida Press, 1997, p. 170</ref>
'''Select list of paintings''' * ''Farmers In Palestine,'' 1958 * ''Ard Halji,'' 1961 * ''Glory to God,'' 1985 * ''Iqraa Bism'' * '' Ikal Wa Tawakkal'' * ''Memory of the First of February: The Arab Unity (study)''
==Awards== * 1948: First prize in Arts in Damascus Exhibition * 1957: First prize at the competition of the city of Naples * 1959: First prize at the competition of Ministry of Culture in United Arab Republic * 1975: Knight Commander Award from the Republic of Italy * 1989: He was awarded the Syrian First Class [[Order of Civil Merit (Syria)|Order of Merit]] by the Syrian Republic after his death.<ref>{{cite web|title=MAHMOUD HAMMAD A SYRIAN MASTER OF ABSTRACT ART (1923-1988)|url=http://www.mahmoudhammad.com/about-1/|website=mahmoud hammad|accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>
