'''Vikramkhol''' also spelled '''Bikramkhol''' ({{lang-or|[[:or:ବିକ୍ରମଖୋଲ|'''ବିକ୍ରମଖୋଲ''']]}}) is a prehistoric archaeological site located near [[Jharsuguda]], [[Odisha]] state, [[India]] and lies in Reserved Forest of Belpahar range, at a distance of 12&nbsp;km from Belpahar. The place is known for prehistoric rock art and rock inscriptions dated around 3000 BCE.
==Inscriptions== The Vikramkhol rock shelter, where the inscriptions found, is dated between 3000 BCE to 4000 BCE. Details about the caves were first published in [[Indian Antiquary]] in 1935 by the efforts of historian K.P.Jayaswal.<ref name=telegraph1>{{cite news| last1=Mohanty| first1=Subrat| title=Ancient rock art starts to fade out - Engravings in Vikramkhol cave under threat| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111228/jsp/odisha/story_14932470.jsp#.VFjaxjSUep4| accessdate=4 November 2014| work=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]]| location=Kolkotta| date=28 December 2011}}</ref> The inscriptions were studied in 1955. The size of the inscriptions is 37 meters in lengths, 5.65 meters in breadth and 8 meters in height.<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Puratatva Indian Archeological Society| date=1996| issue=26| page=35| title=Vikramkhol| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y9ttAAAAMAAJ&q=Vikramkhol&dq=Vikramkhol&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DuRYVLLcDo6DuwSJwYHoAQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwBA| accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> The inscriptions are yet to be studied in detail and some historians link this script to Mohenjedaro script.<ref name=danino>{{cite book| last1=Danino| first1=Michel| title=The Lost River: On The Trail of Saraswati| year=2010| publisher=Penguin| location=London| isbn=978-9351187745| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DZr0AwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+lost+river&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_-FYVNi9L8KLuwS3qYCoAg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Vikramkhol&f=false| accessdate=4 November 2014| subscription=yes}}</ref> It is observed that some of inscriptions are painted and then cut in the rock.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vikramkhol (Bikramkhol) |url=http://www.navratnanews.com/Tourisum/tourist_places_of_jharsuguda.htm |publisher=navaratnanews.com |accessdate=4 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130720033830/http://www.navratnanews.com/Tourisum/tourist_places_of_jharsuguda.htm |archivedate=July 20, 2013 }}</ref> A replica of the inscription is exhibited in [[Odisha State Museum|State Museum]] which helped [[Odia language]] to get Classical Status.<ref name=telegraph2>{{cite news| first1=Namita| last1=Panda| first2=Subrat| last2=MohantyY| title=Scripts fade into oblivion - Vikramkhol inscriptions cited to claim classical tag for Odia| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1130811/jsp/frontpage/story_17217786.jsp#.VFjp-TSUep4| accessdate=4 November 2014| work=The Telegraph| date=4 September 2015}}</ref>
===Neglect=== Some historians have felt that, due to negligence and apathy by Government agencies, the inscriptions are fading out and damaged by vandals. Activities of coal mines in surrounding hills, industries like sponge iron are putting environmental pressure on this prehistoric archeological site.<ref name=telegraph1/> The rock shelter, where the inscriptions are found, is not fully protected and kept open to atmosphere,<ref>{{cite web| title=Rock Art Shelter of Vikramkhol - Vikramkhol - Jharsuguda| url=http://ignca.nic.in/asp/showbig.asp?projid=orgjhar0020001| publisher=Indira Gandhi National Center for Archeology| accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> giving scope for vandals and visitors to deface the inscriptions.<ref>{{cite news| title=Inscriptions on the Vikramkhol rock shelter in Jharsuguda| url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111229/jsp/odisha/story_14938763.html| accessdate=4 November 2014| work=The Telegraph| date=29 December 2011}}</ref> As it is located inside Reserve Forest of Belpahar range, the remote access to the place has also contributed to neglect by Government Agencies.<telegraph2/>
