{{short description|1832 painting by William Etty, inspired by a metaphor in Thomas Gray's poem The Bard}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}
{{featured article}}
{{italic title}}
[[Image:Etty Youth 1832.jpg|right|upright=1.35|thumb|''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm'', 1832,  {{convert|158.7|by|117.5|cm|in|abbr=on}}|alt=Naked people on a boat, naked people in the water around the boat, and a flying naked child blowing on the sails of the boat. And two parrots.]]

'''''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm''''' (also known as '''''Fair Laughs the Morn''''' and '''''Youth and Pleasure''''') is an [[oil painting]] on canvas by English artist [[William Etty]], first exhibited in 1832 and currently in [[Tate Britain]]. Etty had been planning the painting since 1818–19, and an early version was exhibited in 1822. The piece was inspired by a metaphor in [[Thomas Gray]]'s poem ''[[The Bard (poem)|The Bard]]'' in which the apparently bright start to the notorious misrule of [[Richard II of England]] was compared to a gilded ship whose occupants are unaware of an approaching storm. Etty chose to illustrate Gray's lines literally, depicting a golden boat filled with and surrounded by nude and near-nude figures.

Etty felt that his approach to the work illustrated a moral warning about the pursuit of pleasure, but his approach was not entirely successful. ''The Bard'' was about a supposed curse on the [[House of Plantagenet]] placed by a Welsh [[bard]] following [[Edward I of England]]'s attempts to eradicate Welsh culture, and critics felt that Etty had somewhat misunderstood the point of Gray's poem. Some reviewers greatly praised the piece, and in particular Etty's technical abilities, but audiences of the time found it hard to understand the purpose of Etty's painting, and his use of nude figures led some critics to consider the work tasteless and offensive.

The painting was bought in 1832 by [[Robert Vernon (art patron)|Robert Vernon]] to form part of his collection of British art. Vernon donated his collection, including ''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm'', to the [[National Gallery]] in 1847, which, in turn, transferred it to the [[Tate Gallery]] in 1949. It remains one of Etty's best-known works, and formed part of major exhibitions at Tate Britain in 2001–02 and at the [[York Art Gallery]] in 2011–12.

== Background ==
[[File:Etty – The Dawn of Love.jpg|thumb|''[[The Dawn of Love (painting)|The Dawn of Love]]'' (1828) was intended to illustrate [[John Milton]]'s ''[[Comus (John Milton)|Comus]]''.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=116}} By the end of the 1820s, Etty had become notorious for his use of literary and mythological subjects as a pretext for nudity.|alt=A naked woman attempts to wake a sleeping, naked, man]]

[[William Etty]], the seventh son of a [[York]] baker and miller,<ref name="ODNB">{{Cite ODNB|id=8925|title=William Etty}}</ref> had been an apprentice printer in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]].{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=5}} On completing his seven-year apprenticeship at the age of 18 he moved to London "with a few pieces of chalk crayons",{{sfn|Burnage|2011a|p=157}} and the intention of becoming a [[history painting|history painter]] in the tradition of the [[Old Masters]].{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=86}} He enrolled in the Schools of the [[Royal Academy of Arts]], studying under renowned portrait painter [[Thomas Lawrence]].{{sfn|Burnage|2011a|p=157}} He submitted numerous paintings to the Royal Academy over the following decade, all of which were either rejected or received little attention when exhibited.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=31}}

In 1821 Etty's ''[[The Arrival of Cleopatra in Cilicia]]'' (also known as ''The Triumph of Cleopatra'') was a critical success.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=31}} The painting featured [[Nude (art)|<!-- Normally this would be overlinking, but in this context readers are likely to want to learn more about the tradition of nude art -->nude figures]], and over the following years Etty painted further nudes in biblical, literary and mythological settings.<ref name="MAG Etty">{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestergalleries.org/salvaged/the-painting/about-the-artist/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211024806/http://www.manchestergalleries.org/salvaged/the-painting/about-the-artist/index.html|archivedate=2015-02-11|title=About the artist|publisher=Manchester Art Gallery|accessdate=10 February 2015}}</ref> All but one of the 15 paintings Etty exhibited in the 1820s included at least one nude figure.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=32}}

While some nudes existed in private collections, England had no tradition of nude painting and the display and distribution of nude material to the public had been suppressed since the 1787 [[Society for the Suppression of Vice|Proclamation for the Discouragement of Vice]].{{sfn|Smith|2001b|p=53}} Etty was the first British artist to specialise in the nude,{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}} and the reaction of the lower classes to these paintings caused concern<!--among whom??--> throughout the 19th century.{{sfn|Smith|2001b|p=55}} Although his portraits of male nudes were generally well received,{{efn-ua|Etty's male nude portraits were primarily of mythological heroes and classical combat, genres in which the depiction of male nudity was considered acceptable in England.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|pp=32–33}}}} many critics condemned his repeated depictions of female nudity as indecent.<ref name="MAG Etty" />{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=32}}

== Composition ==
{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|salign=right|quote=<poem>
Fair laughs the morn, and soft the zephyr blows,
While proudly riding o'er the azure realm,
In gallant trim, the gilded vessel goes,
Youth on the prow and Pleasure at the helm,
Unmindful of the sweeping whirlwind's sway,
That, hushed in grim repose, expects his evening prey.
</poem>|source=Lines from ''The Bard'' which accompanied ''Youth and Pleasure'' when originally exhibited.<ref name="RAcat">{{cite book|title=The Exhibition of the Royal Academy: The Sixty Fourth|year=1832|publisher=Royal Academy of Arts|location=London|page=15}}</ref>}}

''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm'' was inspired by a passage in [[Thomas Gray]]'s poem ''[[The Bard (poem)|The Bard]]''.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}} The theme of ''The Bard'' was the English king [[Edward I of England|Edward I]]'s conquest of Wales, and a curse placed by a Welsh [[bard]] upon Edward's descendants after he ordered the execution of all bards and the eradication of Welsh culture.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}} Etty used a passage Gray intended to symbolise the seemingly bright start to the disastrous reign of Edward's great-great-grandson [[Richard II of England|Richard II]].{{sfn|Gray|Bradshaw|1891|p=87}}

[[File:William Blake - The Poems of Thomas Gray, Design 60 The Bard 08.jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.9|[[William Blake]]'s treatment ({{circa|1798}}) of the same passage from ''The Bard''. Gray's poem was a popular theme for artists.|alt=A bearded man floats on the sea, with a storm cloud and a sunrise in the background]]

Etty chose to illustrate Gray's words literally, creating what has been described as "a poetic romance".{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}} ''Youth and Pleasure'' depicts a small gilded boat. Above the boat, a nude figure representing [[west wind|Zephyr]] blows on the sails. Another nude representing Pleasure lies on a large bouquet of flowers, loosely holding the [[Tiller|helm]] of the boat and allowing Zephyr's breeze to guide it. A nude child blows bubbles, which another nude on the [[prow]] of the ship, representing Youth, reaches to catch. [[Naiad]]s, again nude, swim around and clamber on the boat.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}} Although the seas are calm, a "sweeping whirlwind" is forming on the horizon, with a demonic figure within the storm clouds.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}}<ref name="Gent1832">{{cite journal|date=June 1832|title=Fine Arts.—Royal Academy|journal=The Gentleman's Magazine|publisher=J. B. Nichols and Son|location=London|volume=33|issue=6|page=539}}</ref> (Deterioration and restoration means this demonic figure is now barely visible.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}}) The intertwined limbs of the participants were intended to evoke the sensation of transient and passing pleasure, and to express the themes of female sexual appetites entrapping innocent youth,{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=67}} and the sexual power women hold over men.{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}}

Etty said of his approach to the text that he was hoping to create "a general allegory of Human Life, its empty vain pleasures—if not founded on the laws of Him who is the Rock of Ages."{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=180}} While Etty felt that the work conveyed a clear moral warning about the pursuit of pleasure, this lesson was largely lost upon its audiences.{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}}

When Etty exhibited the completed painting at the [[Royal Academy Summer Exhibition]] in 1832,{{sfn|Burnage|Bertram|2011|p=24}} it was shown untitled,<ref name="Times">{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Royal Academy |day_of_week=Thursday |date=24 May 1832 |page_number=3 |issue=14860 |column=F }}</ref> with the relevant six lines from ''The Bard'' attached;{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}} writers at the time sometimes referred to it by its [[incipit]] of ''Fair Laughs the Morn''.<ref name="Times" />{{efn-ua|Etty's 2007 biographer Leonard Robinson states that much of this verse was omitted, and the painting was captioned ''Fair laughs the Morn, and soft the Zephyr blows, Youth on the prow, and Pleasure at the helm, That hush'd in grim repose, expects his evening prey''.{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=180}} The original catalogue for the 1832 Summer Exhibition clearly indicates that all six lines accompanied the painting on its original exhibition.<ref name="RAcat" />}} By the time of Etty's death in 1849, it had acquired its present title of ''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm''.<ref>{{cite journal|date=January 1850|title=Obituary.—William Etty, Esq, R.A.|journal=The Gentleman's Magazine|publisher=John Bower Nichols and Son|location=London|volume=33|issue=1|page=98}}</ref>

== Versions ==
[[File:Etty Youth 1822.png|right|thumb|The 1822 version of the painting provoked a strong reaction from ''The Times'' for its supposed indecency.|alt=Gold boat full of naked people]]
[[File:Etty – Three Female Nudes.jpeg|right|thumb|''Three Female Nudes'', attributed to Etty, {{circa|1820}}, is possibly either a study for or derived from ''Youth and Pleasure'', but may be a study for an unrelated work.|alt=three nude women on a rock, with a sea serpent coiling around the rock.]]

The final version of ''Youth and Pleasure'' was painted between 1830 and 1832,<ref name="Tate">{{cite web|url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/etty-youth-on-the-prow-and-pleasure-at-the-helm-n00356|title=William Etty – Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm|publisher=[[Tate]]|date=May 2007|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> but Etty had been contemplating a painting on the theme since 1818–19.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=158}} In 1822 he had exhibited an early version at the [[British Institution]] titled ''A Sketch from One of Gray's Odes (Youth on the Prow)'';{{sfn|Burnage|Bertram|2011|p=22}}{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=178}} in this version the group of figures on the prow is reversed, and the swimmers around the boat are absent.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=158}} Another rough version of the painting also survives, similar to the 1832 version but again with the figures on the prow reversed.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=159}} This version was exhibited at a retrospective of Etty's work at the [[Society of Arts]] in 1849; it is dated 1848 but this is likely to be a misprint of 1828, making it a preliminary study for the 1832 painting.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=159}}

Although it received little notice when first exhibited, the 1822 version provoked a strong reaction from ''[[The Times]]'':

{{quote|We take this opportunity of advising Mr. Etty, who got some reputation for painting "Cleopatra's Galley", not to be seduced into a style which can gratify only the most vicious taste. Naked figures, when painted with the purity of Raphael, may be endured: but nakedness without purity is offensive and indecent, and on Mr.&nbsp;Etty's {{sic|hide=y|canvass}} is mere dirty flesh. Mr.&nbsp;Howard,{{efn-ua|[[Henry Howard (artist)|Henry Howard]], one of Etty's rivals in the field of history painting.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=31}}}} whose poetical subjects sometimes require naked figures, never disgusts the eye or mind. Let Mr.&nbsp;Etty strive to acquire a taste equally pure: he should know, that just delicate taste and pure moral sense are synonymous terms.|''The Times'', 29 January 1822<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Lord Gwydyr |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=29 January 1822 |page_number=3 |issue=11466 |column=A }}</ref>}}

An [[oil sketch]] attributed to Etty, given to York Art Gallery in 1952 by [[Judith Hare, Countess of Listowel]] and entitled ''Three Female Nudes'', is possibly a preliminary study by Etty for ''Youth and Pleasure'', or a copy by a student of the three central figures.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=159}} Art historian Sarah Burnage considers both possibilities unlikely, as neither the arrangement of figures, the subject matter or the [[sea serpent]] approaching the group appear to relate to the completed ''Youth and Pleasure'', and considers it more likely to be a preliminary sketch for a now-unknown work.{{sfn|Burnage|2011c|p=215}}

== Reception ==
''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm'' met with a mixed reception on exhibition, and while critics generally praised Etty's technical ability, there was a certain confusion as to what the painting was actually intended to represent and a general feeling that he had seriously misunderstood what ''The Bard'' was actually about.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}} ''The Library of the Fine Arts'' felt "in classical design, anatomical drawing, elegance of attitude, fineness of form, and gracefulness of grouping, no doubt Mr. Etty has no superior", and while "the representation of the ideas in the lines quoted [from ''The Bard''] are beautifully and accurately expressed upon the canvas" they considered "the ulterior reference of the poet [to the destruction of Welsh culture and the decline of the [[House of Plantagenet]]] was entirely lost sight of, and that, if this be the nearest that Art can approach in conveying to the eye the happy exemplification of the subject which Gray intended, we fear we must give up the contest upon the merits of poetry and painting."<ref name="Library1832">{{cite journal|date=July 1832|title=Exhibition of the Royal Academy|journal=Library of the Fine Arts|volume=4|issue=18|publisher=M. Arnold|location=London|page=57}}</ref> Similar concerns were raised in ''The Times'', which observed that it was "Full of beauty, rich in colouring, boldly and accurately drawn, and composed with a most graceful fancy; but the meaning of it, if it has any meaning, no man can tell", pointing out that although it was intended to illustrate Gray it "would represent almost as well any other poet's fancies."<ref name="Times" /> ''[[The Examiner (1808–86)|The Examiner]]'', meanwhile, took issue with the cramped and overladen boat, pointing out that the characters "if not exactly jammed together like figs in a basket, are sadly constrained for want of room", and also complained that the boat would not in reality "float half the weight which is made to press upon it."{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}}

Other reviewers were kinder; ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine]]'' praised Etty's ability to capture "the beauty of the proportion of the antique", noting that in the central figures "there is far more of classicality than is to be seen in almost any modern picture", and considered the overall composition "a most fortunate combination of the ideality of Poetry and the reality of Nature".<ref name="Gent1832" /> The ''[[Athenaeum (British magazine)|Athenæum]]'' considered it "a poetic picture from a very poetic passage", praising Etty for "telling a story which is very difficult to tell with the pencil".<ref>{{cite journal|date=26 May 1832|title=Fine Arts; Exhibition at Somerset House|journal=The Athenæum|publisher=J. Holmes|location=London|issue=239|page=340}}</ref>

The greatest criticism of ''Youth and Pleasure'' came from ''[[The Morning Chronicle]]'', a newspaper which had long disliked Etty's female nudes.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=33}} It complained "no decent family can hang such sights against their wall",{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=129}} and condemned the painting as an "indulgence of what we once hoped a classical, but which are now convinced, is a lascivious mind", commenting "the course of [Etty's] studies should run in a purer channel, and that he should not persist, with an unhallowed fancy, to pursue Nature to her holy recesses. He is a laborious draughtsman, and a beautiful colourist; but he has not taste or chastity of mind enough to venture on the naked truth." The reviewer added "we fear that Mr.&nbsp;E will never turn from his wicked ways, and make himself fit for decent company."{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=33}}

== Legacy ==
[[File:Youth & Pleasure handbill.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Gratuitous nudity made ''Youth and Pleasure'' a popular piece for [[tableau vivant]] performances, at the time the only form of live entertainment in which nudity was permitted.|alt=Handbill advertising "Madame Warton's performance of Youth on the Prow and Pleasure at the Helm"]]
''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm'' was purchased at the time of its exhibition by [[Robert Vernon (art patron)|Robert Vernon]] for his important collection of British art.{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}}{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=158}} (The price Vernon paid for ''Youth and Pleasure'' is not recorded, although Etty's cashbook records a partial payment of £250—about £{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|250|1832|r=-3}}|0}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} terms{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}—so it is likely to have been a substantial sum.{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=159}}) Vernon later purchased [[John Constable]]'s ''The Valley Farm'', planning to hang it in the place then occupied by ''Youth and Pleasure''. This decision caused Constable to comment "My picture is to go into the place—where Etty's "[[Bumboat]]" is at present—his picture with its precious freight is to be brought down nearer to the nose."{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}}{{efn-ua|Art historians differ in their interpretation of Constable's reaction, and whether he was expressing surprise or pleasure that Vernon was moving ''Youth and Pleasure'' to a less prominent position to make way for ''The Valley Farm''.{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}}{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=181}}}} Vernon presented his collection to the nation in 1847, and his 157 paintings, including ''Youth and Pleasure'', entered the [[National Gallery]].{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=388}}

When [[Samuel Carter Hall]] was choosing works to illustrate his newly launched ''[[The Art Journal]]'', he considered it important to promote new British artists, even if it meant illustrations which some readers considered pornographic or offensive. In 1849 Hall secured reproduction rights to the paintings Vernon had given to the nation and soon published and widely distributed an engraving of the painting under the title ''Youth and Pleasure'',{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=181}} describing it as "of the very highest class".{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=69}}

Needled by repeated attacks from the press on his supposed indecency, poor taste and lack of creativity, Etty changed his approach after the response to ''Youth on the Prow, and Pleasure at the Helm''.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=36}} He exhibited over 80 further paintings at the Royal Academy alone, and remained a prominent painter of nudes, but from this time made conscious efforts to reflect moral lessons.{{sfn|Burnage|2011d|p=42}} He died in November 1849 and, while his work enjoyed a brief boom in popularity, interest in him declined over time, and by the end of the 19th century all of his paintings had fallen below their original prices.{{sfn|Robinson|2007|p=440}}

In 1949 the painting was transferred from the National Gallery to the [[Tate Gallery]],{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=158}} where {{asof|2015|lc=y}} it remains.<ref name="Tate" /> Although ''Youth and Pleasure'' is one of Etty's best-known paintings,{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=63}} it remains controversial, and Dennis Farr's 1958 biography of Etty describes it as "singularly inept".{{sfn|Farr|1958|p=63}} It was one of five works by Etty chosen for [[Tate Britain]]'s landmark ''Exposed: The Victorian Nude'' exhibition in 2001–02,{{sfn|Smith|2001a|p=57}} and also formed part of a major retrospective of Etty's work at the [[York Art Gallery]] in 2011–12.{{sfn|Burnage|2011b|p=128}}

